```
### Test Reporting and Parallel Execution
#### `reporting/index.js`
This module creates a custom reporter to save test results and screenshot metadata in a JSON file.
```javascript
class CustomReporter {
  onRunStart(context, data) {
    this.testResults = [];
  }

  onTestStart(test, runnable) {
    this.currentTest = { name: test.title, description: runnable.parent.title };
  }

  onTestDone(test, results) {
    const screenshotFiles = glob.sync(`**/*.png`, { cwd: Cypress.config('screenshotsFolder') });
    const screenshots = screenshotFiles.map((file) => {
      const metadata = file.replace(`${Cypress.config('screenshotsFolder')}\\/`, '');
      const testNameParts = this.currentTest.name.split(' - ');
      return {
        testName: testNameParts[0],
        testDescription: testNameParts[1],
        filePath: file,
        outcome: results.state,
      };
    });
    this.testResults.push(...screenshots);
  }

  write() {
    fs.writeFileSync('test-results.json', JSON.stringify(this.testResults, null, 2));
  }
}

module.exports = CustomReporter;
```
#### `tasks/start-cypress.js`
This task starts Cypress with parallel testing enabled.
```javascript
const { execSync } = require('child_process');
const { config } = require('@cypress/config');

execSync(`npx cypress run --config ${JSON.stringify(config)} --parallel`);
```
#### `tasks/stop-cypress.js`
This task stops the Cypress process.
```javascript
const { execSync } = require('child_process');
execSync('pkill -9 node');
```
### Usage
To run the tests, execute the following commands in your terminal:

1. Build the Docker images by running `docker-compose build`.
2. Start the services with `docker-compose up`.
3. Run the tests using `npm run start-cypress`.
4. Stop the Cypress process with `npm run stop-cypress`.

After the tests have completed, you'll find a `test-results.json` file containing information about each test run, including screenshot metadata.

This framework provides a robust testing environment that leverages Docker for isolation and Cypress's screenshot capabilities for detailed reporting. It also utilizes parallel testing to speed up your test suite and includes a custom reporter to store test results and screenshot metadata in a structured format.

Below is a comprehensive C++ solution that defines a function `markdownToHtml()` to convert Markdown to HTML using the existing libraries `rapidjson`, `ft2pool/htmlparser` for HTML formatting and `SmartyPants` spirit-like approach for Markdown parsing spirit inspirations but utilizing only Boost Spirit X3 for simplicity and ease here employs only `fmt` for formatted string literals. Here it includes three major parts: Markdown parsing, conversion rules, and HTML building.

Firstly, install required libraries:
- For building, you'll need `boost-spirit-v3-devel` (Boost Spirit X3), `fmt` and a C++17 compliant compiler.
- You'll also need to clone the GitHub repository of enquirer/CmarkSharp (a C++ implementation of CommonMark/Markdown spec) and replace the provided implementation below with its parsing part.

Here's the implementation:
```cpp
#include <string>
#include <stdexcept>
#include <sstream>
#include <iomanip>
#include <boost/spirit/home/x3.hpp>
#include "cmark/cmark.h"

namespace markdown_to_html {
using namespace std;
using namespace boost::spirit::x3;

struct html_escape {
    std::string& str;
    auto& f = *this;

    template<typename T>
    void operator()(char c) const {
        if ((c >= 'a' && c <= 'z') || (c >= 'A' && c <= 'Z') ||
            (c >= '0' && c <= '9') || c == '.' || c == ',' || c == '!')
            str += c;
        else {
            ostringstream oss;
            oss << "&#"x << setw(4) << setfill(static_cast<unsigned int>('0')) << hex << static_cast<int>(c);
            str += oss.str();
        }
    }

    html_escape(std::string& s) : str(s) {}
};

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& input) {
    std::string html;
    char output[CMARK_OPTION_DEFAULT_SOFT_BREAKS | CMARK_OPTION_ENABLE_TABLES];

    std::unique_ptr<cmark_parser, void (*)(cmark_parser*)> parser(cmark_parser_new(), cmark_parser_free);
    if (!cmark_parse(&output, strlen(CMARK_TRANSFORM_HTML), input.c_str(), input.size(), parser.get())) {
        throw runtime_error("Markdown parsing failed");
    }

    std::string escaped;
    html_escape esc(escaped);

    auto html_start = *"" << "<html><head><meta charset='utf-8'><title>Converted MD</title></head><body>";
    auto html_end = *</body></html>";

    bool in_code_block = false;
    bool in_link = false;
    string current_link_text;
    string current_link_href;

    auto html_rule = (
        *((
            ('<' >> -(html_escape, !alnum >> *space >> ';')) |
            ('&' >> (
                ('&') | ('amp;'[html_escape]) | ('quot;'[html_escape]) | ('apos;'[html_escape]) |
                ("lt;"[html_escape]) | ("gt;"[html_escape])
            ))
            )
        >> space |
            ('[' >> +(graph - ']([' >> -(escapespace >> ']')) ']')[
                in_link = true,
                current_link_text = _1,
                !(peek("]("))
            ] |
            (!in_code_block >> ("```"[this_blanks >> _] >> +(graph - "```"[this_blanks]))[
                in_code_block = true;
                esc |= html_escape
            ] |
            (!in_link && !in_code_block >> (+graph)[esc])
        )%
        (
            ((in_link) [
                if (!current_link_href.empty()) {
                    html += "<a href=\"" + current_link_href + "\">" + current_link_text + "</a>";
                    current_link_href.clear();
                    current_link_text.clear();
                    in_link = false;
                }
            ] |
            ((in_code_block) [esc = [](auto& c){}; in_code_block = false])
        ) |
            (("\n" >> -(space >> '\n'))[
                html += "<br>";
                esc = html_escape{escaped};
            ] |
            ('\n'[html += "<p>" + escaped + "</p>\n"; escaped.clear()])
        )
    );

    string md_input(input);

    auto r = phrase_parse(
        begin(md_input), end(md_input),
        html_rule,
        space,
        ascii_space);

    if (!r) throw runtime_error("Markdown parsing failed");

    html.insert(html.begin(), html_start);
    html += "\n";
    html += escaped.str();
    html += "\n";
    html.insert(html.end(), html_end);

    if (!current_link_href.empty()) {
        html.replace(html.find("<body>"), html.find("<body>") + 6, "<body>" +
            "<a href=\"" + current_link_href + "\">" + current_link_text + "</a>");
    }

    return html;
}
}

int main() {
    std::string md = "# Hello World\nThis is a [link](https://example.com). \n```\nCode block\n```";
    std::string html = markdown_to_html(md);
    cout << "Markdown:\n" << md << '\n';
    cout << "Converted HTML:\n" << html << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```
In this implementation, we utilize the Cmark library for parsing Markdown and Boost Spirit X3 for HTML escaping. We define a custom HTML escaping rule to replace special characters with their HTML entities. The main function `markdownToHtml` processes the Markdown text into HTML while handling specific cases like links and code blocks.

This code assumes you have all necessary libraries installed and configured properly. If you want to use the provided CmarkSharp implementation instead of linking against the system Cmark library, you'll need to integrate its parsing logic into the given `markdownToHtml` function.

